textPath.tspan: Two coastal micropredators from the Devonian reaching 2m, Pycnosteus and Tartuosteus, were the largest

text.textPath: Birds reached a maximum size of 2m with Anthropornins, a penguin from the Paleogene

textPath.tspan: The Cambrian Anomalocaris canadensis and Amplectobelua symbrachiata are the earliest marine megafauna, which were coastal, pelagic predators reaching 1m

text.textPath: The largest invertebrate was the Jurassic Seirocrinus subangularis, a coastal, filter-feeding crinoid reaching 15m
The largest and earliest mammalian megafauna was Basilosaurus, a 20m predator from the Paleogene living in both coastal and oceanic waters
The largest fish was the 16.5m Leedsichthys problematicus, an oceanic filter feeder from the Jurassic
The largest chondrichthyan was the 20m Otodus megalodon, a coastal, pelagic, active-predator from the Neogene
The largest marine megafauna was the 21m ichthyosaur Shonisaurus sikanniensis, a pelagic predator living in the open oceans of the Triassic

textPath.tspan: Glyptaspis verrucosa was the largest Placoderm
